mso-bidi-font-family:David'>Cleaning data<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-top:0in;margin-right:3.0in;margin-bott=
om:8.0pt;
margin-left:3.0in;line-height:150%'><span style=3D'font-size:12.0pt;line-he=
ight:
150%;font-family:"Georgia",serif;mso-bidi-font-family:David'>This study is
based on the <u><a
href=3D"https://data.montgomerycountymd.gov/Public-Safety/Traffic-Violation=
s-API/y8ms-hri9/data">data</a></u>
provided by the Montgomery county government. The data contains several fea=
tures,
but the most important information is in the <i style=3D'mso-bidi-font-styl=
e:
normal'>Description</i> column. For each violation, traffic officers keep a
note of the violations as text. Depending on the writing style of police
officers, variation in the details, context of the violation and typos, sim=
ilar
violations has been noted in different format. Just as an example, the use =
of
telephone has been written in several ways below. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-top:0in;margin-right:3.0in;margin-bott=
om:8.0pt;
margin-left:3.0in;line-height:150%'><span style=3D'font-size:12.0pt;line-he=
ight:
150%;font-family:"Georgia",serif;mso-bidi-font-family:David;color:blue;
background:white'>DRIVER USING HANDS TO USE HANDHELD TELEPHONE WHILEMOTOR
VEHICLE IS IN MOTION</span><span style=3D'font-size:12.0pt;line-height:150%;
font-family:"Georgia",serif;mso-bidi-font-family:David;color:blue'><br>
<span style=3D'background:white'>DRIVER USING HANDS TO USE HANDHELD TELEPHO=
NE
WHILE MOTOR VEHICLE IS IN MOTION</span><br>
<span style=3D'background:white'>HOLDER OF LEARNER'S PERMIT 18 Y/OLDER USIN=
G A
HANDHELD TELEPHONE WHILE OPER. M/V&nbsp;</span><br>
<span class=3DGramE><span style=3D'background:white'>.....</span></span><br>
<span style=3D'background:white'>.....</span><br>
<span style=3D'background:white'>HOLDER OF PROVISIONAL LIC 18 Y/OLDER USING=
 A
HANDHELD TELEPHONE WHILE OPER. M/V</span><br>
<span style=3D'background:white'>DRIVER USING HANDS TO USE HANDHELD TELEPHO=
NE</span><br>
</span><span style=3D'font-size:12.0pt;line-height:150%;font-family:"Georgi=
a",serif;
mso-bidi-font-family:David'>Technically, the computer understands text as a
string and even a typo or an extra space between words is considered as a d=
ifferent
value. A smarter way to translate computer into a language it can understan=
d is
to convert the text into a mathematical representation. I used word
vectorization method � a natural language processing tool � to convert the =
text
into an array containing binary numbers. This method first selects the most
relevant words, i.e. the words that carry the most crucial information. For
example, in the texts above, removing �TELEPHONE� or �HANDHELD� alters sign=
ificantly
the meaning of the text, whereas the words such as �A� and �IN� have a litt=
le value
to the meaning of the text. Such high relevant words serve as a word token.
Then it converts the text as an array of numbers each number representation=
 the
presence of word in the string. <span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>�</span><s=
pan
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>�</span><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-top:0in;margin-right:3.0in;margin-bott=

ist
of most common mistakes listed in the ascending order and in the semantic l=

used by police officers. The largest number of violations occur due to the =
driver�s

and license protects you a lot from being pulled over. This can easily be d=

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-top:0in;margin-right:3.0in;margin-bott=
om:8.0pt;
margin-left:3.0in;line-height:150%'><span style=3D'font-size:12.0pt;line-he=
ight:
150%;font-family:"Georgia",serif;mso-bidi-font-family:David'>My friend <i
style=3D'mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Mr. XYZ</i> is really a bad driver but=
 is
always scared of traffic citations. He wants to know what types of violation
are more likely to get a citation. To help him predicting whether he gets
citation after he gets pulled over after a <span class=3DGramE>particular
violation</span>, I run some statistical models using machine learning
techniques. <span class=3DGramE>For the purpose of</span> making a model, I=
 first
separated the data into two sets: The first set of data � called <b
style=3D'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><i style=3D'mso-bidi-font-style:norma=
l'>Training
data</i></b> � is data that the statistical model receives. Using the data
features (values of the data) and outcomes (citation or warning), the model
builds the best mathematical equation that captures the trends in the data.=
 I
can check the accuracy of the model on another set of data � called <b
style=3D'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><i style=3D'mso-bidi-font-style:norma=
l'>Test
data</i></b>. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-top:0in;margin-right:3.0in;margin-bott=

ight:
150%;font-family:"Georgia",serif;mso-bidi-font-family:David'>I tested sever=
al
learning methods shown in the table below to achieve the better prediction.=
 As
expected, none of the models are 100 % accurate and there are wrong predict=
ions
that cannot be avoided. In statistics, the best way to quantify wrong predi=
ctions
are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Precision_and_recall">Precisio=
n,
Recall</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F1_score">f1-score=
</a>,
the details of which are beyond the scope of this blog. The accuracy of mod=
el (fraction
of correct predictions) is given by ROC score. The table provides a compari=
son
of the quality of models under different models.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
